# Spatial dimension

## Statement

The number of large spatial dimensions is

$$d \;=\; 3.$$

This is the dimension of the SL(2, R) manifold committed to in
[`sl2r_manifold`](sl2r_manifold.md), as computed in
[`three_dimensions`](three_dimensions.md) and singled out by the
[Bianchi characterization](lie_group_characterization.md).

## Derivation

Carried by [`three_dimensions`](three_dimensions.md).  The mediant
action on Farey pairs extends to $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ in
the continuum; the Klein-quotient substrate consistently selects
$d = 3$ via its surviving denominator class $q_3 = 3$.  Both
independent routes agree, as observed in
[Proof C](proof_C_bridge.md) §B3.

## Observational status

$d = 3$ is consistent with every laboratory and astronomical test
of spatial geometry to present precision:

- Submillimeter inverse-square-law tests (Hoyle 2004 and successors)
  bound extra compact dimensions to wavelengths $\lesssim 50\,\mu m$.
- Large-scale galaxy-clustering and CMB observations are consistent
  with $d = 3$ on cosmological scales.

The framework does not predict $d \ne 3$ at any scale.  Any
experimental detection of extra dimensions would falsify the
claim.

## Remarks

- "Exact" here means structural: the prediction is an integer, not
  a fit.  It is the dimension of a specific Lie group picked out
  by a specific topology commitment.
- The companion claim that spacetime signature is $(3, 1)$ is
  carried in [`lorentz_symmetry`](lorentz_symmetry.md).
